'''Esmeralda Ribeiro''' (born 1958) is a [[Brazil]]ian journalist and writer of [[Africa]]n descent.<ref name=oliveira>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=nTxKJzC1DQ4C&pg=PA219 |title=Writing Identity: The Politics of Contemporary Afro-Brazilian Literature |page=219 |last=Oliveira |first=Emanuelle |year=2008 |ISBN=1557534853 |publisher=Purdue University Press}}</ref>
She was born in [[São Paulo]] and studied journalism at the [[University of São Paulo]]. Ribeiro became a member of [[Quilombhoje]], an Afro-Brazilian literary group, in 1982.<ref name=oliveira/> Her first poems appeared in the 1982 anthology ''Cadernos negros'' (Black notebooks); her first short story "Ogun" appeared in the 1985 anthology. She later worked with [[Marcio Barbosa]] as editor for ''Cadernos negros''.<ref name=duke/> Her work was translated into English for the collections ''Moving Beyond Boundaries, International Dimension of Black Women's Writing'' and ''Enfim...Nos/Finally...Us: Escritoras Negras Brasileiras Contemporaneas/Contemporary Black Brazilian Women Writers'', both published in 1995.<ref name=oliveira/>
In 1988, she published a short novel ''Malungos e milongas''.<ref name=duke>{{cite book |url=https://books.google.ca/books?id=Bs4b8Dqlf74C&pg=PA130 |title=Literary Passion, Ideological Commitment: Toward a Legacy of Afro-Cuban and Afro-Brazilian Women Writers |pages=130–32 |last=Duke |first=Dawn |year=2008 |ISBN=0838757065}}</ref>
Ribeiro has also worked for the [[São Paulo (state)|São Paulo state]] Secretary of Culture.<ref name=oliveira/>
